I"¿<h2 id="private-key-and-csr">Private key and CSR</h2>
<p>First, the private key and a <em>Certificate Sign Request</em> (CSR) have to be generated.</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>openssl req <span class="nt">-out</span> &lt;DOMAIN&gt;.csr <span class="nt">-newkey</span> rsa:4096 <span class="nt">-nodes</span> <span class="nt">-keyout</span> &lt;DOMAIN&gt;.key
</code></pre></div></div>

<blockquote>
  <p><strong>Note:</strong> All fields can be empty, except Common Name! It needs to be the exact domain name for which the certificate is intended for.</p>
</blockquote>

<h2 id="sign-csr">Sign CSR</h2>
<blockquote>
  <p><strong>Note:</strong> There are two options here:</p>
</blockquote>

<ol>
  <li>The CSR could be signed by an <strong>official CA</strong> (like <a href="https://www.startssl.com">StartSSL</a>, see <a href="/startssl-certificate-validation"><em>here</em></a>), or</li>
  <li><strong>Self-signed</strong>. The self-signed certificate will cause a warning in the browser. To self-sign a CSR, execute:
    <div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>openssl x509 <span class="nt">-req</span> <span class="nt">-days</span> 365 <span class="nt">-in</span> &lt;DOMAIN&gt;.csr <span class="nt">-signkey</span> &lt;DOMAIN&gt;.key <span class="nt">-out</span> &lt;DOMAIN&gt;.crt
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
</ol>

